{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016qWhXqt5iNhBmjYR2cDK5K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of all three bugs. Let me fix them:\n\n**Bug 1: cc_extract_text jq -rs fails on truncated/non-JSON lines**\n- Current: `jq -rs '...' \"$log_file\"` — slurp mode fails if any line is invalid JSON\n- Fix: Pre-filter lines to only pass valid JSON, using `grep -v '^$'` and then process line by line, or use `while read line; do echo \"$line\" | jq ...; done`\n- Best approach: Use `jq -R 'try fromjson catch null | select(. \n\nI'm filtering out invalid JSON lines before processing them through jq, either by pre-filtering empty lines and then using a try-catch pattern to skip malformed entries, or by processing the log file line-by-line to handle truncated content gracefully. splits it by newline, filters out invalid JSON entries, then processes the valid ones—this handles truncated lines gracefully. For the sed issue on macOS, I should use perl instead since BSD sed doesn't handle `\\x1b` the same way, or rely on bash's `$'...'` quoting to convert the escape sequence before passing it to sed.\n\nNow I'm looking at a couple more bugs: spawn.sh needs to pass the interval value as a JSON field, and retry.sh has an integer comparison that might fail if the interval isn't properly retrieved. Looking at the actual code flow, `cc_task_get` returns an empty string successfully when the field isn't found, so the `|| echo 0` fallback doesn't trigger—`INTERVAL` ends up as `\"\"`. But then `[[ -n \"$INTERVAL\" ]]` evaluates to false for an empty string, which short-circuits the rest of the condition chain, so the integer comparison never actually runs. Let me trace through what's actually causing the crash in the bug report. I'm realizing the issue: when `cc_task_get` returns an empty string, `jq` exits with code 0, so the `|| echo 0` fallback never triggers—`INTERVAL` stays empty. The user's error message suggests `[[ '' -gt 0 ]]` is somehow being evaluated despite the `[[ -n \"$INTERVAL\" ]]` guard, which shouldn't happen with short-circuit logic, unless there's something about how bash is parsing or evaluating this on their system. I'm realizing the issue might be more subtle with bash's `set -euo pipefail` — the `[[` compound operator does short-circuit, so if the first condition fails, the second part shouldn't evaluate. But I should just add the `${INTERVAL:-0}` guard to be safe and ensure the field is properly initialized in spawn.sh.\n\nNow I'm going to implement the fixes. First, I need to update the jq invocation in lib.sh to handle invalid JSON lines more robustly by reading the file as raw text, splitting by newlines, and parsing each line individually.\n\nFor the ANSI stripping, I'm switching from sed to perl to handle the escape sequences more reliably.\n\nNow I need to add the interval field to spawn.sh by passing it as a JSON argument to jq, and make sure retry.sh has a safe default for the INTERVAL variable before using it in comparisons. Let me apply all these fixes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10669,"cache_read_input_tokens":16812,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10669},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"493fb87d-5bdf-4877-a927-bd41d6d235b6","uuid":"322fb347-74e2-4c6a-9370-7d39a6cbf11c"}
